# Cursor Coding Rules

## C# Rules
- Never use yield statements inside try-catch blocks (error CS1626)
- Avoid nested try-catch blocks when possible
- Don't suppress exceptions without proper handling
- Ensure all disposable resources are properly managed

## General Rules
- Follow existing project code style and conventions
- Add appropriate comments for complex logic
- Keep methods small and focused on a single responsibility
- Use meaningful variable and method names
- Don't duplicate code - extract reusable methods

## Architecture Rules
- Maintain proper separation of concerns
- Don't mix UI logic with business logic
- Keep network operations properly encapsulated
- Follow established project patterns for error handling 